<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/b4a9587e274be191b4edc0231198d3a7> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "XYLOFOON MET 25  TOETSEN EN 22 KALEBAS-KLANKKASTEN" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/b4a9587e274be191b4edc0231198d3a7> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "The balafon is made of wood with large gourd resonators under the wooden bars. The balafon is a tuned percussion instrument and the sound is produced by striking the wooden keys with padded sticks or beaters. This instrument is a fixed-key balafon where the keys are strung and tied to a frame with calabash or gourd resonators of various sizes underneath. The calabashes are fixed below in arrays from small to large.  The balafon is usually constructed with 17 to 21 rectangular wooden slats, arranged from low to high notes.\r\n\r\nSometimes the instrument is strapped around the neck and can be played standing up. This instrument is more likely to be played by a seated musician. In most cases a single player hits multiple keys with two mallets. Sometimes balafon players wear belled bracelets on each wrist to accentuate the sound of the keys. The balafon is often played in an ensemble with the kora and drums.\r\n\r\nPre-colonial music in Senegal was dominated by the Griot tradition - the itinerant poet-musician who is the custodian of historical cultural knowledge dominated the making of music. (The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music, Volume 1: Africa - p.419).\r\n\r\nOther instruments, similar to the balafon, include the modern classical orchestral xylophone with its hard wooden bars, and the glockenspiel with its thinner metal bars. Jazz artists sometimes play vibrophones, a more robust version of the balafon with full-bodied metal bars. Indonesia has the gamelan and in Latin America the marimba is played. These instruments are both percussive and melodic. They play tuned rhythmic patterns.\r\n\r\nThe balafon was originally found in West Africa but is now found throughout the world. The popularity of the balafon has seen a resurgence since the 1980s in the growth of African Roots Music and World Music. Contemporary Senegalese music is known as mbalax - or percussion based music. This genre includes a combination of Cuban rhythms and kora-based traditional melodies sung in a high-pitched style. The most famous contemporary performer of Senegalese music is Youssou N'Dour (The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music, Volume 1: Africa p.421-22). The distinctive sound and traditional style of the balafon has also been exported to western instruments.  \r\n\r\nThe title of the Senegalese National Anthem is Pincez Tous vos Koras, Frappez les Balafons (Everyone strum your koras, strike the balafons). \r\n\r\n\r\nVervaardiging\r\nDeze xylofoon heeft 25 gestemde toetsen (lamellen), waaronder 22 kalebas-klankkasten hangen. (In de kalebassen zijn waarschijnlijk gaatjes gemaakt die met een membraantje zijn afgeplakt; dit geeft een zoemend geluid, waardoor het 'mirlitons' zijn, en membranofonen.) De grootte van de toetsen en de kalebassen bepaalt de toonhoogte en het timbre. Het geheel is in een houten raamwerk geplaatst.\r\n\r\n<STRONG><a href=\"http://collectie2.wereldculturen.nl/othermedia/Audio/AUD000136.mp3\" target=\"_blank\">Beluister de xylofoon.</a></STRONG>"^^<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#HTML> .
